Date : 15-06-2026 (Python Introduction, Installation Process and Variables)

Python was released in the year 1991 by Guido van Russom (version 0.9)

What is Python ?

High-level language 
Object Oriented Programming (OOP's)
Interpreted Language (The code will be executed line by line that's the reason python is called a Interpreted language)
Dynamically Typed Language (No need of mentioning the kind of the datatype pass to the variable)

Why is Python widely used or recommended to be used ?

Easy to Learn & Understand
Less Syntax
Cross Platform 
Open Source
Wide range of Libraries

Commenting of the Lines :

Single Line commenting (#) - Used to explain lines in the code
Multiple Line commenting (''' ''' OR """ """) - Used to write the explanation of multiple lines

Variables and Their Rules :

These are used to store the datatypes

Rules : 

It can start with a ( _ , small letters, capital letters, and mixing of the letters, numbers and special characters )
It can't start with a number and special character
The variables can't have whitespaces while being declared but instead we can use a underscore (_) to eliminate those whitespaces


Boolean Type :


These are used to show whether a particular condition is "True" or "False"

Example : 

num , num2 = 9, 89
print(num == num2) # False
print(num != num2) # True

Multiple variables with multiple values ( add , = , )
Multiple variable with single value ( add = = )

Swapping variable values without temp variable

a , b = 50, 70 
a , b = b, a
print(a, b)

Date = 16/07/2026 (Tokens and types of tokens)

Tokens :

Tokens are the smallest individual parts or units of the program

Types :

Keywords  (The reserved or the pre-defined words which are the loaded into the IDLE)
Identifiers (These are the variables , function name, class names which are defined by the user while writing the code for the program)
Operators (These are the arithmetic, logical operations which can be performed on the variables used in the program)
Literal (These are the data values which are assigned to the variables in the declaration of the values) 

Types of Operators :

Arithmetic (+,*,-,/,**,//,%) Example : print(8+7,8*7,8-7,8*9,8**9,8%9,8//9) Output : 15 56 1 72 134217728 8 0
Assignment (=,==,+=,-=,/=)
Comparison (!=, ==,>=,<=,<,>)
Logical (AND, OR, NOT)

Identity (IS, IS NOT) Example : a = [1,2] b = [1,2] print(a is b) print(a == b) Output : False True 
(The is operator search for the object at its particular memory address and doesn't check what is stored inside the memory location while the " == " operator checks for the values stored in the memory location)

Membership (IN, NOT IN)
Bit-wise (These operators perform the calculations on the binary values of the variables)

Types of the Bit-wise Operators :

& - Bit-wise AND 
| - Bit-wise OR
^ - Bit-wise 
<< - Bit-wise Left Shift
>> - Bit-wise Right Shift

Date = 17-07-2026 (Datatypes and it's types)

To find what type of datatype the variable is storing we need to use the keyword " type " to see the category
To find where the variable stores in the memory we need to use the keyword " id " to find the memory address

Datatypes :

Integer - int (Arithmetic Operations)
Decimal - float (Arithmetic Operations)
String - (It is a sequence of characters that are enclose in ' ', " ", ''' ''' and it is immutable)
Lists - (It is a collection of different datatypes like int, float, string, list inside a list, tuple inside a list and these are represented using a "[ ]" and separated by ' , ', also 	they are mutable)

Methods of string datatype :

replace() --  It is used to replace old string with a new string in the program (Syntax : variable_name.replace("old string", "new string", "number of times we want to replace)) 
reverse() --  It is used to reverse the string					(Syntax : variable_name.rev())
split()	  --  It is used to split the original string into substrings 		(Syntax : variable_name.split("on what basis"))
join()	  --  It is used to add a new character after every substring of prog   (Syntax : 'new variable'.join(variable_name))
index()   --  It is used to return the position value of a character of str	(Syntax : variable_name.index('character to passed'))
count()	  --  It is used to count the occurance of a character in the str	(Syntax : variable_name.count('character to passed','staring range', 'ending range'))
indexing()--  It is used to return the substring which is present in a position (Syntax : variable_name[index number])
isupper() --
islower() --

Methods of list datatype:

append()  --  It is used to add or give a new element to the existing list and it will added at the last index of the list (Syntax : variable_name.append(value))
extend()  --  It is used to add only iterative elements like list, tuple, dictionaries to the existing list at the end pos (Syntax : variable_name.extend(list))
remove()  --  It is used to remove the first occurrence of the value in the list & if it's not in the list is throws error (Syntax : variable_name.remove(value))
pop()	  --  It is used to remove a particular value which is present in the specified or if no value is mentioned last value is popped and if the value is not found it throw list out of 	     20range error (Syntax : variable_name.pop(value, index))

Write 3 complex indexing programs (Assessment) 

sample = [[1, 2], 'coding', [10.5, ['AI', (7, 8, 9), ['Data', 55]], 100], 'SQL', [(5, 6), ['Cloud', ['AWS', 999]], 12]]
print(sample[4][1][1][1])


demo = [5, ['HTML', [10, 20, ['CSS', (1.1, 2.2), 'JS']], 30], 'Python', [[100, 'AI'], ['ML', [200, 300, ['Deep Learning', 400]]], 500], (600, 700)]
print(demo[3][1][1][2][0])


practice = [
    1,
    'Python',
    [2, 3.5, ['Java', (10, 20), ['HTML', ['CSS', 99]]]],
    ['AI', [100, (200, [300, 'ML'])]],
    ('End', 500)
]

99 - print(practice[2][2][2][1][1])
ML - print(practice[3][1][1][1])
20 - print(practice[2][2][1][1])
['Java', (10, 20), ['HTML', ['CSS', 99]]] - print(practice[2][2])


Date : 18-07-2026 (Tuples & Dictionaries)

Tuple : (It is a collection of different datatypes like int, float, string, list inside a list, tuple inside a list and these are represented using a "( )" and separated by ' , ', also 	they are immutable)
Dictionaries : (It is a collection of different datatypes like int, float, string, list, tuple and these are represented using a "{ }", key and values are separated by ' : ', all the things present on the left side are called the keys and the things which are present on the right side are values , also they are immutable)

Methods of tuple datatype :

count() -- Syntax : variable_name.count(item)
index() -- Syntax : variable_name.index(item)


Declaring a Dictionary (Syntax) :

dec = { 1 : "gautham", 'surname' : "K", "sal" : 150000, 2 : 90 } # Used as databases

Methods of dictionary datatype :
 
keys  -- It is used to access all the keys which are defined in the dictionary and returns the output in the form of tuple (Syntax : variable_name.keys())
values -- It is used to access all the values which are stored in the keys of the dictionary and returns the output in the form of tuple (Syntax : variable_name.values())
items -- It is used to return or display all the pairs of keys and values present in the dictionary and returns the output in the form of tuple (Syntax : variable_name.items())
update -- It is used to modify a exsisting value or add a value inside the dictionary (Syntax : variable_name.update({'key name' : 'value'}))
clear  -- It is used remove all the pairs of keys and values from a dictionary (Syntax : variable_name.clear())
get  -- It is used to retrive a value of a particular key and returns the value stored in the key (Syntax : variable_name.get('key value'))

# Set operation and methods And Type Conversions 

Set -- It is an unordered collection of elements and it doesn't allow duplicate values inside it , they are mutable and they are represented in "{ }"

Methods of set datatype :

update -- It is used to add new elements or values to the declared set (Syntax : variable_name.update([values]))
add -- It is used to a new elements or values to the declared set (Syntax : variable_name.add(value))
remove -- It is used to remove a element from the declared set and in case if the value is not present in the set it throws KeyError(Syntax : variable_name.remove(value))
discard -- It is used to remove a element from the declared set and in case if the value is not present in the set it doesn't throw an error(Syntax : variable_name.discard(value))
pop -- It is used to remove a element from the declared set (i.e random value)and in case if the value is mentioned it throws PositionArgumentalError(Syntax : variable_name.pop())


Operation in the set datatype :


Union -- It is used to add or combine two sets with set values but does not allow duplicates in the combined output (Syntax : set1.union(set2) or set1 | set2)
Intersection -- It is used to show the common set values present in two sets (Syntax : set1.intersection(set2) or set1 & set2)
Difference -- It is used to show the difference between two sets or it returns set values which are present in the first set but not in the second set (Syntax : set1.difference(set2) or set1 - set2)

Type Conversions :

The process of converting from one datatype to another is called type conversion there are two types of type conversion one is implicit and explicit type conversion 

Explicit Conversion :

Integer () : 

'''
variable = str(integer)
nine = 69
print(type(nine))
s1 = str(nine) # For Converting integer to string
s2 = float(nine) # For converting integer to float
print(s1, s2, type(s1), type(s2))
'''

Float() :

'''
nin = 69.8
print(type(nin))
d1 = str(nin) # For converting float to string
d2 = float(nin) # For converting float to integer
print(s1, s2, type(d1), type(d2))
'''

String() :

Integer -- int(value) # it can only convert the integer values which are individually specifies but if they are present inside a sentence it throws and error
Float -- float(value) # it can only convert the float values which are individually specifies but if they are present inside a sentence it throws and error

Example :
'''
a,b = "98","102.5"
print(type(a), type(b))
w, z = int(a), float(b)
print(type(w), type(z))
'''

List -- list(value)
Tuple -- tuple(value)

Example :

'''
am = "1,'python',[2,['python',9],4],'java',['python',[56,78],'java',90]"
print(type(am))
y = list(am)
print(y, type(y))

af = "1,'python',[2,['python',9],4],'java',['python',[56,78],'java',90]"
h = tuple(af)
print(h, type(h))

'''
List :

string -- str(value) 
tuple -- tuple(value)
